% v2 draft — addition to §3.5 (Empirical Studies of Multi-Agent
% Failure). Brief paragraph after the silobench2026 mention to
% introduce τ²-bench as the public benchmark we evaluate on.

$\tau$-bench~\cite{taubench2024} and its successor
$\tau^2$-bench~\cite{tau2bench2025} (Sierra Research) provide
state-validated conversational-agent benchmarks: each trial passes
only if the agent's final database state matches the state produced
by replaying the task's reference action sequence.  Redundant or
wrong-state side-effecting calls therefore register as scoring
failures intrinsically, rather than via a separately defined process
metric.  $\tau^2$ reports pass$^k$, the fraction of tasks where all
$k$ independent trials succeed---a reliability metric that rewards
cross-trial coordination directly when peer state can be shared.
We use $\tau^2$-bench retail as the head-to-head benchmark for the
pull-vs-intercept architectural comparison
(\S\ref{sec:eval:results:retail-intercept}).

